### Which @angular/* package(s) are relevant/related to the feature request?

elements

### Description

Currently we need a way to communicate between host application and web element. We need to extend NgElement with some methods of our components.

I suggest to extend NgElementConfig with exposedMethods property, that accept array of keys of public component methods.

I'll submit a pull request soon.

### Proposed solution

```typescript
type ExtractPublicMethods<T> = {[K in keyof T]: T[K] extends (...args: unknown[]) => unknown ? K : never}[keyof T];

export type NgElementConfig<T = any, E extends ExtractPublicMethods<T> = ExtractPublicMethods<T>> = {
  /**
   * An optional custom strategy factory to use instead of the default.
   * The strategy controls how the transformation is performed.
   */
  strategyFactory?: NgElementStrategyFactory;

  /**
   * An optional list of methods to expose as public methods on the custom element.
   */
  exposedMethods?: Array<E>,
}
```

### Alternatives considered

We found another solution:

```typescript
@Component(...)
export class MyWebComponent {
    private readonly elementRef = inject(ElementRef);

    constructor() {
        this.elementRef.nativeElement.open = this.open.bind(this);
    }

    public open(): void {...}
}
```

But it looks ugly, especially when a lot of methods needs to be exposed.

### Which @angular/* package(s) are relevant/related to the feature request?

compiler-cli, common, core

### Description

In react we can possible made super simple components

```ts
export function FavoriteColor() {
  const [color, setColor] = useState("red");

  return (
    <>
      <h1>My favorite color is {color}!</h1>
      <button
        type="button"
        onClick={() => setColor("blue")}
      >Blue</button>
    </>
  )
}
```

What if we have in the future like this?


### Proposed solution


```ts
// angular/core
function useState(defaultState: T) {
  const state = signal(defaultState);
  const handle = (val: T) => state.set(val);

  return [state, handle];
}

// ....

import { useState } from '@angular/core';

export function FavoriteColor() {
  const [color, setColor] = useState("red");

  return `
      <h1>My favorite color is ${color()}!</h1>
      <button
        type="button"
        (click)="${setColor("blue")}"
      >Blue</button>
    `;
}
```

and then in any place

```html
<FavoriteColor />
```

**Benefits**:

- Selectorless
- For simple component we have less boilerplate
- Template interpolation

### Alternatives considered

Nothing idea

[Type attribute reference](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTML/Reference/Elements/button#type)

This small change is primarily intended to simplify filtering for a submit button in a form.

```ts
// Before
MatButtonHarness.with({ selector: '[type="submit"]' });

// After (buttonType avoids conflict with the reserved keyword, type)
MatButtonHarness.with({ buttonType: 'submit' });
```
